defaultProposaldefault&#xa0;default•default&#xa0;defaultThe functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other organisations operating between the Secretadefaultry of State and individual schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in support for schools at this level;defaultA well run and effective local education authority will have good knowledge of its local schools – based 
defaulton contact with parents and young people and, in the case of maintained schools, the active role of a school improvement partner.
defaultExamples of such authorities are Tower Hamlets and Hackney, both of whom have transformed their schools from being at or near 
defaultthe bottom of the league tables 
default(10 years ago) 
defaultto, despite high levels of deprivation, being in the top half. Tower Hamlets has done so almost entirely without academies. Hackney built four new academies and most of the secular secondary schools are now ac
defaultademies. (A mark of 
defaultit
defaults success is that the only schools that are 
defaultnotdefault now oversubscribed are the faith schools in the borough.)
defaultHowever Hackney has played an active role even in its academies. It administers all admissions (though different schools have di
defaultfferent banding rules and some have faith requirements), ensuring that pupils only have to take one banding test. All schools work together, whether Academies or maintained, and the LEA seeks to provide support and challenge to all 
defaultit
defaults schools.
defaultThat is key
default. Local authorities have found that, when they express concern to the DfE about an academy, the DfE is only actively involved if the school is below the national floor targets. A good local authority will be aware, for instance, if a school is above floor 
defaulttargets but coasting. 
defaultA local authority is not doing its job if it first finds out that a school is under-performing after an Ofsted inspection. 
defaultThere will always be many good and outstanding schools, whether they are academies or maint
defaultained schools. The 
defaultissue is which body 
defaultis there to step in i
defaultf a school starts to weaken, which body
default is best able to spot it and who can best intervene to help.
defaultThe need for a “middle tier” is widely recognised and the DfE has responded by creating a new layer, with Commissio
defaultners. It is unclear how effective this will be, how well one individual in a region will be able to know their local schools.
