defaultProposal: default&#xa0;default•default&#xa0;defaultWhat alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to failing primary schools.defaultIf the local authority is supportive, 
defaultcould 
default“failing” primary schools access support from the local authority and be able to improve within the community of maintained schools.
defaultExample: Snaresbrook school in East London was threatened with forced academisa
defaulttion after an Ofsted visit in June 2013. 
defaultIn
default the meantime the local authority, Conservative-controlled Redbridge Council, had intervened, brought in a new head, provided an estimated £50k of support and, by all accounts
default,
default 
defaultturned the 
defaultschool round.
defaultThe vocal 
defaultopposition of parents to academisation was supported by Redbridge Council, including all its Conservative members. The DfE responded by stating that the parents could get their wish and the school would remain in the maintained sector.
defaultThe school had been 
defaultoffered the chance to join an academy chain of two schools. It is hard to see how a newly established, and small, academy chain could be of greater benefit than a well-resourced local authority, with several dozen schools and the resources to second an exp
defaulterienced headteacher into the school. 
defaultIs this an isolated example? Analysis of the school-by-school data released by the DFE in December 2013 reveals:
defaulthttp://bit.ly/1bE3L09defaulthttp://bit.ly/1hXllEIdefaultThere is no evidence base for conversion of primary schools to academies. It is an experiment and there is, so far, no data in the public domain to detail
default whether it is a success or not.
default 
defaultIn contrast there is substantial evidence of the improvement that maintained primary schools are capable of. An underperforming primary can draw on the substantial resources and experience of the local authority.
